@RiverMersey Yes what you've effectively reconstructed is a flow battery, and they certainly work (every battery has its trade offs). The beauty of the architecture suggested here is that it's very cost effective, low maintenance, and very energy dense. This battery would grow dendrites - but they won't penetrate the ceramic in use as the separator here, so it's moot. They could form all day and it's not going to be a problem, in fact this battery would also effectively self regenerate overtime, the dendrites would just dissolve back into the solution as it discharges.

The problem with this design with being totally regenerative is the off gassing. If you could get the hydrogen evolution at the anode to go back to the cathode (or possibly inverse their positioning in the cell itself, causes it's own new set of problems with self discharge) it would dissolve back into solution too. And you'd end up with a battery that might last a thousand years!

What Mr. Murray doesn't do a fantastic job of really explaining (although he does indeed mention it briefly) is that the power density of this battery and it's efficiency would be quite low but that's definitely a problem that could be overcome by spending some more time dealing with the conductivity of the cathode. But you could store a ton of energy in it, it wouldn't degrade by being left at 0%, wouldn't fuss if you over charged it at all, and would self-regenerate if you took some care with the anode and cathode setups.

@DavidPaulNewtonScott what is "partition coefficient"?  I've never heard that term.
Does that have to do with something's affinity to prefer one solvent over another between two phases (like oil and water)? That was one of the things I initially thought was the reason to put oil in a bromine battery..
  Yes , bromine is NOT something to play around with willy nilly, PPE is a must. I've dabbled with it a bit , can tell you, one drop on your hand , you wash it off immediately, but even after washing your hands for 10 minutes, if you rub your eyes it's like getting hit with tear gass, even after washing. I could see how a spill could take days to completely clear up. Nasty stuff.
